6. HOW CODEX MUST WORK ON THIS PROJECT
====================================================================

Every V3.5 slice implementation must follow these rules:

1. MODIFY THE EXISTING CODEBASE
Do not create a new app.
Do not redesign the entire UI.
Do not replace major architecture or routing.

2. USE MINIMAL, SURGICAL CHANGES
Prefer local, targeted edits.
Avoid large rewrites unless a component is clearly broken or impossible to adapt safely.

3. PRESERVE VISUAL LANGUAGE
Reuse existing design system, spacing, typography, badges, cards, tabs, colors, and interaction patterns.

4. KEEP DEMO-SAFE
The prototype may use demo/mock/local data.
If backend logic is absent, create only minimal safe demo-layer support.

5. AVOID BACKEND DEPENDENCIES
Do not assume backend endpoints will change.
Do not introduce API contract changes unless the slice absolutely requires a local, non-breaking stub/adapter.

6. CENTRALIZE WHERE SENSIBLE
If a repeated pattern is being fixed in multiple places, prefer a small helper or utility instead of duplicating logic everywhere.

Examples:
- formatBabyDisplayName(...)
- isNewCase(...)
- orderedCaseStatuses(...)
- validateParentPhoneFields(...)
- shouldShowProcessType(...)

7. DO NOT SILENTLY CHANGE PRODUCT LOGIC
If a requested change crosses from UI/demo into business-rule redesign, implement only what the slice explicitly allows.

8. REPORT CHANGES CLEARLY
At the end of each slice implementation, report:
- files changed
- what was done
- any assumptions
- any non-blocking ambiguities

9. NO SCOPE CREEP
Only implement the requested slice.
Do not opportunistically bundle adjacent future slices.

====================================================================
7. GLOBAL UI / UX CONVENTIONS FOR V3.5
====================================================================

Apply these conventions consistently whenever relevant:

A. NAMING
Prefer “Baby of <Mother Name>” as the standard display pattern.
Use “BO - <Mother Name>” only where a compact card/list layout clearly requires the shortened form.

B. HOSPITAL-FACING SIMPLICITY
Hide internal routing/process jargon from hospital users wherever the relevant slice calls for it.

C. STATUS PRESENTATION
When ordered display is needed for the V3.5 surfaces, prefer this order:
- Under Review
- Returned
- Approved
- Rejected
- Closed

If other statuses still exist internally, they may remain in data/state, but the visible order on the touched screens should respect the above where applicable.

D. VALIDATION STYLE
Use concise, human-readable validation messages.
Do not use alarming or legalistic wording.
Block submit when required, but keep the user informed clearly.

E. HIGHLIGHTS / BADGES
Use subtle badges or indicators.
Avoid flashy animation or loud visual noise.

F. DEMO DATA HONESTY
Do not let stale sample data make correct UI appear broken.
Clean or normalize demo data where required.

G. TEXT / LABEL CLARITY
If wording conflicts with agreed direction, align labels/help text to the agreed interpretation.

